In article <kpkmjcINNc01@neuro.usc.edu> merlin@neuro.usc.edu (merlin) writes:
>What I need from the network is a
>technique for enciphering the data for each database with a different key
>so that my clients can only read my database -- and clients from the other
>companies can only read their database.
>[...] the cost of
>penetrating the algorithm should be quite high -- say about $10K to $20K.

DES is quite adequate for this purpose.

>Also, it would be nice if the cryptographic technique permitted the use of
>a secondary key (client name) to generate a challenge sequence which must
>be answered with a unique key (to be provided by the vendor to each client)
>so that one client's key would not unlock the database for another client.


Are you planning to make custom CDROMs?

If two CDROMs are identical and the machines reading them are identical,
there is no way to disstinguish one user from the other so there is no
way to rule out the wrong client's key.
